INSERT INTO `physquiz` VALUES (1,'What is the primary function of the female urethra?','To transport urine out of the body','To store urine until excretion','To regulate hormone levels','To carry reproductive cells','To transport urine out of the body','Explanation:\r\nThe female urethra is a short tube that connects the urinary bladder to the external opening called the urethral meatus. Its primary function is to transport urine stored in the bladder out of the body during urination. Unlike the male urethra, which serves both urinary and reproductive functions, the female urethra is solely involved in the excretion of urine. This process is essential for removing waste products and maintaining the body\'s fluid and electrolyte balance.','2024-11-18 12:39:34','2025-01-14 16:49:39',1,50,NULL,'To regulate the flow of urine within the bladder',NULL),(2,'What is the primary site of filtration in the kidneys?','Ureter','Glomerulus','Bladder','Renal pelvis','Glomerulus','Explanation: \r\nThe glomerulus is a network of tiny capillaries located in the nephron, the functional unit of the kidney. It is the primary site where blood filtration occurs. As blood flows through the glomerulus, waste products, excess water, and small molecules are filtered out of the blood and collected in the Bowman\'s capsule. This filtered fluid eventually becomes urine after further processing in the nephron.','2024-11-18 16:19:15','2024-11-29 13:21:16',1,50,NULL,'',NULL),(3,'What is the main function of the renal pelvis in the kidney?','To filter blood and remove waste','To store urine temporarily before it leaves the body','To collect urine from the nephrons and funnel it to the ureter','To concentrate urine through reabsorption','To collect urine from the nephrons and funnel it to the ureter','Explanation:\r\nThe renal pelvis is a funnel-shaped structure located at the center of the kidney. It collects urine produced by the nephrons (through the calyces) and channels it into the ureter for transport to the bladder, for storage and eventual excretion.','2024-11-18 16:29:20','2025-01-08 17:59:12',1,50,NULL,'To provide structural support to the kidney',NULL),(4,'Where does urine production primarily occur in the kidney?','Renal pelvis','Nephrons','Ureter','Renal Cortex','Nephrons','Explanation:\r\nUrine production primarily occurs in the nephrons, which are the functional units of the kidney. Each nephron consists of a glomerulus for blood filtration and a tubular system for reabsorbing water and nutrients while concentrating waste into urine. This process involves three main steps: filtration, reabsorption, and secretion.','2024-11-18 16:32:38','2025-01-08 17:54:48',1,50,NULL,'Renal medulla',NULL),(5,'What is the powerhouse of the cell','Mitochondrion','Lysosome','Golgi apparatus','Vacuole','Mitochondrion','Which organelle is responsible for energy production in the cell?\r\nThe mitochondrion is often referred to as the \"powerhouse\" of the cell because it generates ATP through cellular respiration, providing energy for cellular activities.','2024-11-28 17:40:26','2025-01-14 19:15:25',1,45,NULL,'Nucleus',NULL),(6,'What is the primary role of the nucleus in a cell?','Protein synthesis','Genetic information storage and regulation','Detoxification of harmful substances','Breaking down cellular waste','Genetic information storage and regulation','The nucleus houses the cell\'s DNA, which contains the instructions for making proteins and regulating cellular activities. It is the control center of the cell.','2024-11-28 17:42:15','2025-01-08 17:47:05',1,45,NULL,'Transporting materials across the cell',NULL),(7,'What is the jelly-like substance inside the cell where organelles are suspended?','Cytosol','Nucleus','Endoplasmic reticulum','Ribosome','Nucleus','Cytosol is the semi-fluid component of the cytoplasm in which organelles are suspended. It allows for the movement of materials within the cell and is involved in cellular processes.','2024-11-28 17:47:54','2025-01-08 17:45:25',1,45,NULL,'Mitochondrion',NULL),(8,'Which cellular structure is involved in protein synthesis?','Ribosome','Centriole','Vacuole','Peroxisome','Centriole','Ribosomes are responsible for translating mRNA into proteins. They can be found floating freely in the cytosol or attached to the rough endoplasmic reticulum.','2024-11-28 17:49:24','2025-01-08 17:44:24',1,45,NULL,'Smooth endoplasmic reticulum',NULL),(9,'In this image of kidney filtration, where is the Loop of Henle.','A','B','C','D','C','Loop of Henle is long U-shaped portion of the tubule that conducts urine within each nephron of the kidney.','2025-01-08 17:38:07','2025-01-10 18:12:44',1,55,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/glomerulusDiagram.png','E',NULL),(10,'Which endocrine gland is responsible for the secretion of growth hormone?','Pancreas','Pituitary','Thyroid','Ovaries','Pituitary','none yet','2025-01-08 17:33:04','2025-01-08 17:33:08',28,48,NULL,'Adrenal',NULL),(11,'When prescribing hormone based drugs it is important to think about routes of administration. Which format is therefore suitable for insulin, a non-steroidal hormone?','Food supplement','Tablet','Injection','Liquid','Injection','none yet','2025-01-08 17:32:17','2025-01-08 17:32:21',28,48,NULL,'Lozenge',NULL),(12,'Which hormonal mechanism of action classically involves receptor autophosphorylation?','Receptor Tyrosine Kinases','G-Protein Coupled Receptors','Steroid Hormone-Receptor Complexes','All of the above','Receptor Tyrosine Kinases','Receptor Tyrosine Kinases is......','2025-01-08 17:30:31','2025-01-08 17:31:19',28,48,NULL,'None of the above',NULL),(13,'Long portal veins are present in which region of the hypothalamic-pituitary axis?','Hypothalamus','Paraventricular Nuclei','Posterior lobe','Infundibulum','Infundibulum','none yet','2025-01-08 17:27:10','2025-01-08 19:59:40',28,48,NULL,'Anterior lobe',NULL),(14,'Secretion of IGF-1 is principally promoted by which hormone?','Growth hormone','Somatostatin','Growth hormone releasing hormone','Adrenocorticotrophic hormone','Adrenocorticotrophic hormone','none yet','2025-01-06 17:18:11','2025-01-08 17:18:15',28,48,NULL,'Testosterone',NULL),(15,'Which enzyme is principally responsible for iodination?','Amylase','Thyroid peroxidase','Iodothyronine deiodinase','Lipase','Thyroid peroxidase','none yet','2025-01-08 17:14:34','2025-01-08 17:14:38',28,48,NULL,'Lysosomal protease',NULL),(16,'Thyroid hormones act through what broad mechanism of action?','Transmembrane transporter','G protein coupled receptor','Receptor tyrosine kinases','None of the above, thyroid hormones cross the membrane passively without assistance','Transmembrane transporter','none yet','2025-01-08 17:12:26','2025-01-08 17:12:31',28,48,NULL,'Second messenger systems',NULL),(17,'Levothyroxine, a treatment for hypothyroidism, is a synthetic analogue of what?','T3','T4','TSH','TRH','T4','none yet','2025-01-06 17:10:40','2025-01-08 17:10:46',28,48,NULL,'Iodine',NULL),(18,'Which layer of the adrenal gland produces mineralocorticoids?','Capsule','Zona glomerulosa','Sona reticularis','Medulla','Zona glomerulosa','none yet','2025-01-06 17:05:10','2025-01-08 19:58:59',1,48,NULL,'Zona fasiculata',NULL),(19,'Production of aldosterone is stimulated by which component of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS)?','Renin','Angiotensinogen','Angiotensin II','Aldosterone','Angiotensin II','none yet','2025-01-08 16:59:26','2025-01-08 16:59:30',1,48,NULL,'Angiotensin I',NULL),(20,'What can be the most serious consequence of prolonged glucocorticoid delivery?','Glucocorticoid toxicity','Resistance to activity','Suppression of the hypothalamic-pituitary axis','Mineralocorticoid activity','Suppression of the hypothalamic-pituitary axis','none yet','2025-01-08 16:58:59','2025-01-08 16:59:02',28,48,NULL,'Glucocorticoid addiction',NULL),(21,'Pituitary Cushing Syndrome is initially caused by excessive secretion of what?','Cortisol','Corticotrophin releasing hormone','Adrenocorticotrophic hormone','Corticotropes','Adrenocorticotrophic hormone','to be added','2025-01-08 17:24:14','2025-01-08 17:24:35',28,48,NULL,'Acetylcholine',NULL),(22,'Which blood vessel carries oxygenated blood away from the heart?','Pulmonary vein','Pulmonary artery','Aorta','Superior vena cava','Aorta','The aorta is the largest artery in the body and carries oxygenated blood from the left ventricle of the heart to the rest of the body. It plays a crucial role in systemic circulation.','2025-01-08 19:57:31','2025-01-08 19:57:35',1,49,NULL,'Inferior vena cava',NULL),(23,'Which type of muscle is responsible for voluntary movement?','Cardiac muscle','Skeletal muscle','Smooth muscle','Ligaments','Skeletal muscle','Skeletal muscles are attached to bones and are responsible for voluntary movements. They are controlled by the somatic nervous system and allow activities such as walking, running, and lifting objects.','2025-01-08 20:02:30','2025-01-08 20:02:35',1,54,NULL,'Tendons',NULL),(24,'Where does gas exchange primarily occur in the lungs?','Bronchi','Bronchioles','Alveoli','Trachea','Alveoli','Gas exchange primarily occurs in the alveoli, which are tiny air sacs in the lungs. Oxygen diffuses from the alveoli into the blood, while carbon dioxide diffuses from the blood into the alveoli to be exhaled. Their thin walls and extensive capillary network facilitate efficient gas exchange.','2025-01-08 20:05:15','2025-01-08 20:05:18',1,51,NULL,'Pleura',NULL),(25,'Which organ is primarily responsible for nutrient absorption?','Stomach','Small intestine','Large intestine','Pancreas','Small intestine','The small intestine is the primary site of nutrient absorption. Its inner lining is covered with villi and microvilli, which increase the surface area for efficient absorption of nutrients like carbohydrates, proteins, fats, vitamins, and minerals into the bloodstream.','2025-01-08 20:08:11','2025-01-08 20:08:14',1,52,NULL,'Liver',NULL),(26,'What is the primary function of the ovaries in the female reproductive system?','To produce and transport eggs to the uterus','To store and release mature eggs (ova)','To produce estrogen and progesterone','To support the development of a fertilized egg','E (Both B and C)','The ovaries have two primary functions: they produce and release eggs (ova) during ovulation, and they produce hormones like estrogen and progesterone, which regulate the menstrual cycle and support pregnancy.','2025-01-08 20:10:50','2025-01-08 20:10:54',1,53,NULL,'Both B and C',NULL),(27,'What is homeostasis in the context of physiology?','The ability of cells to divide and reproduce','The maintenance of a stable internal environment despite external changes','The process of converting food into energy','The regulation of organ function by the nervous system','The maintenance of a stable internal environment despite external changes','Homeostasis is a fundamental concept in physiology. It refers to the body\'s ability to maintain a stable internal environment (e.g., temperature, pH, and blood glucose levels) through regulatory mechanisms, ensuring optimal function despite fluctuations in the external environment.','2025-01-08 20:15:09','2025-01-10 15:52:06',1,44,NULL,'The movement of substances across cell membranes',NULL),(28,'What is the functional unit of the nervous system?','Dendrite','Axon','Neuron','Synapse','Neuron','The neuron is the functional unit of the nervous system. It is specialized to transmit electrical and chemical signals, enabling communication between different parts of the body and the brain.','2025-01-09 14:59:37','2025-01-09 14:59:41',1,46,NULL,'Glial cell',NULL),(29,'Which part of the brain is responsible for regulating balance and coordination?','Cerebrum','Cerebellum','Medulla oblongata','Hypothalamus','Cerebellum','The cerebellum, located at the back of the brain, plays a critical role in regulating balance, posture, and coordination of voluntary movements. It ensures smooth and precise motor activities.','2025-01-09 15:01:20','2025-01-09 15:01:26',1,46,NULL,'Pons',NULL),(30,'What are the 7 steps of the digestive system?','Ingestion and Propulsion','Absorption','Mechanical  and Chemical digestion','Defecation','Ingestion and Propulsion, Mechanical  and Chemical digestion, Absorption and Defecation.','The human digestive system consists of the gastrointestinal tract plus the accessory organs of digestion. Digestion involves the breakdown of food into smaller and smaller components, until they can be absorbed and assimilated into the body.','2025-01-13 15:00:25','2025-01-15 14:26:10',1,52,'https://brighton.cloud.panopto.eu/Panopto/Pages/Viewer.aspx?id=77904e14-2362-495f-acce-ae9e00a8cb82','All of the above',NULL),(31,'learn about the pituitary glad','Hypothalamus','Pituitary stalk','Pituitary portal system','Anterior Lobe','pituitary glad','the parts of the pituitary gland and its relation to the hypothalamus','2025-01-15 20:20:59','2025-01-16 14:04:14',1,55,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/PituitartyGland1.jpg','Poster Lobe','image'),(32,'Thyroid Hormones','0','0','0','0','0','Thyroid Hormones test slide','2025-01-21 17:10:55','2025-01-22 13:59:43',1,57,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/ThyroidGland.pdf','0','pdf'),(33,'204 Module Discussion 2024 Alabama and Extrauterine Children','0','0','0','0','204 discussion','Alabama and Extrauterine Children','2025-01-22 13:52:53','2025-01-22 13:58:16',28,57,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/204 Module Discussion 2024 Alabama and Extrauterine Children.pdf','0','pdf'),(34,'Glucose homeostasis and pathophysiology of diabetes','0','0','0','0','0','T1 L15_ Glucose homeostasis and pathophysiology of diabetes, 9_4_24, OGS','2025-01-22 13:56:50','2025-01-22 13:56:56',28,57,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/T1 L15_ Glucose homeostasis and pathophysiology of diabetes, 9_4_24, OGS.pdf','0','pdf'),(38,'larynx_with_muscles_and_ligaments','0','0','0','0','larynx_with_muscles_and_ligaments','larynx_with_muscles_and_ligaments','2025-03-03 18:18:17','2025-03-03 18:18:49',24,58,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/larynx_with_muscles_and_ligaments.glb','0','3d-model'),(39,'pharynx_and_floor_of_mouth','0','0','0','0','pharynx_and_floor_of_mouth','3D pharynx_and_floor_of_mouth','2025-03-19 17:26:20','2025-03-19 17:27:09',24,58,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/pharynx_and_floor_of_mouth.glb','0','3d-model'),(40,'epithelium of the colon','0','0','0','0','epithelium of the colon','Copyright Sieben Medical Art:\r\nThe model shows the epithelium of the colon. This model is made as part of my final project for the MSc Medical Art and is part of an online resource about epithelium: www.epithelium3d.com Or have a look at the article that was written about it: https://doi.org/10.1080/17453054.2017.1332480','2025-03-24 12:07:47','2025-03-24 12:09:16',28,58,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/epithelium_of_the_colon-2.glb','0','3d-model'),(43,'Gastric wall','0','0','0','0','Layers of the Alimentary Canal','Gastrointestinal wall layers taken from an image by Goran tek-en\r\nLayers of the Alimentary Canal. The wall of the alimentary canal has four basic tissue layers: the mucosa, submucosa, muscularis, and serosa.\r\nGoran tek-en\r\nCreated: 2 March 2014\r\nUploaded: 24 October 2024\r\nCC BY-SA 4.0','2025-04-11 18:26:17','2025-04-11 17:37:06',28,58,'https://placements.bsms.ac.uk/storage/gastric_wall.glb','0','3d-model'),(45,'BSMS Monthly Lecture: Neurophysiology in Action','1','1','1','1','1','1','2025-07-09 09:50:28','2025-07-09 08:51:00',7,11,NULL,'1',NULL);
